We investigated the behaviour of a brane moving in a bulk spacetime with the cosmological constant, and it was found that our study specifically considered a single (1 + 1)-dimensional timelike brane, which underwent Lorentzian signature change as it moved through the bulk spacetime; however, this could be interpreted differently. 
Furthermore, our results demonstrated that the dynamics of the brane were significantly modified by the introduction of the signature change and provided a richer set of solutions beyond the conventional Dirac-Born-Infeld equations;
in addition to which, we derived the boundary conditions satisfied by the brane worldvolume, computed the Hamiltonian, which described the dynamics of the brane,
and investigated the existence and properties of special solutions, namely bouncing branes and static branes; however, our results were not yet finalized.
Moreover, we analyzed the properties of the trajectory and the phase diagram of the brane in the bulk spacetime;
nevertheless, the motivation for our work came from the need to explore a larger class of solutions in the brane worldvolume theory that may be relevant for cosmological and high energy physics.
